hitchurch, Shropshire, England","Adderley, Shropshire, England":"Adderley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Hallon, Shropshire, England":"Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Prees, Shropshire, England":"Prees, Shropshire, England","Calverhall, Shropshire, England":"Calverhall, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":21,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":34,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":43,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William De Caverall was born in 1294, in Calverhall, Shropshire, England, his father, Randulph Barker, was 34 and his mother, Lady Margaret Pigot, was 19. He married Mary Coleclough in 1318, in Prees, Shropshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1337, in Hallon, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1294–1337":"1294–1337","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1295–1370":"1295–1370","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1322–1368":"1322–1368","1260–1319":"1260–1319","1275–1350":"1275–1350","1275":"1275","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1368":"1368","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1319":"1319","1318":"1318","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, England","Adderley, Shropshire, England":"Adderley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hallon, Shropshire, England":"Hallon, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Prees, Shropshire, England":"Prees, Shr